title: Grateful Dead Live at Radio City Music Hall on 1980-10-23
description:
Set 1

On The Road Again, It Must Have Been The Roses, Dark Hollow, Jack A Roe, Cassidy, China Doll, Monkey & The Engineer, Ain't No Lie-> Ripple

Set 2

Feel Like A Stranger, Tennessee Jed, Mama Tried-> Mexicali Blues, Althea, Little Red Rooster, Big Railroad Blues, The Music Never Stopped

Set 3

Samson & Delilah, Ship of Fools, Estimated Prophet-> Terrapin Station-> Drums-> The Wheel-> Truckin'-> Wharf Rat-> Sugar Magnolia, E: Casey Jones

First Set Acoustic

reviews.review_text: Grateful Dead vs New York To my ear, this is the best sounding version on the archive btw.  I guess the schmuck who likes to see his music more than hear it, who keeps yelling "sit down" throughout the acoustic set is more prominent in the other recordings.  Anyway, he's not the only one yelling but I think it gives the recording an element of authenticity, (particularly if you are from the more civilized Boston area and occasionally went to NYC to see shows...ah yes, the burly yelling and whistling of the highly enthusiastic New York heads!)  What I love about it though is the band, especially Jerry, is determined to ignore the prodding from the crowd and play a very, very mellow show.  Jerry whispers his way through his first set material and gives the crowd no mind.  Check out "Oh Babe it Ain't No Lie" for an example of this.  One interesting thing is that "On the Road Again" starts like an Aiko Aiko with drums being the most prominent sound initially.  Cool versions of all the first set tunes.  Stage energy picks up slightly in the second set though Jerry is determined to keep things on simmer. This makes for a highly focused, laid back "Tennessee Jed".  The mellow approach is taken to new levels for the "Terrapin" which is practically somnambulent but quite nice.  This is a tea and toast Grateful Dead show.  Definitely not one that would lead you to expect a "Casey Jones" encore.  Not explosive, but deliberate and very very nice.   Even the loud New Yorkers pipe down for the most part by drums.
